{"action": "edit", "code": "def change_boundary_and_replace_color(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a n*m grid with multiple color pixels and goes through all the pixels.\n    If the current pixel is in the boundary, only consider the pixel within the boundary. \n    If a pixel is black and one of the eight surrounding pixels is non-black and non-blue, \n    the color of that surrounding pixel is assigned to the current pixel.\n    If a row contains three colors or more, and there is only one color, record the color as tcolor. \n    Traverse all the pixels in the new line, if a pixel is blue, change the pixel above it to tcolor.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n,m) representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (n,m) representing the output grid with the boundary pixels changed and color replaced.\n    \"\"\"\n    n, m = input_grid.shape\n    output_grid = np.copy(input_grid)\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(m):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == black:\n                for x in range(max(0, i - 1), min(n, i + 2)):\n                    for y in range(max(0, j - 1), min(m, j + 2)):\n                        if input_grid[x][y] != black and input_grid[x][y] != blue:\n                            output_grid[i][j] = input_grid[x][y]\n                            break\n    for i in range(1, n):\n        row_colors = set(input_grid[i])\n        if len(row_colors) >= 3:\n            tcolor = None\n            for color in row_colors:\n                if color != blue:\n                    if tcolor is None:\n                        tcolor = color\n                    else:\n                        tcolor = None\n                        break\n            if tcolor is not None:\n                for j in range(m):\n                    if input_grid[i][j] == blue:\n                        output_grid[i - 1][j] = tcolor\n    return output_grid\ndef change_boundar