{"action": "edit", "code": "def change_boundary_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a n*m grid with multiple color pixels.\n    It goes through all the pixels, and if the current pixel is in the boundary, only consider the pixel within the boundary.\n    If a pixel is black and one of the eight surrounding pixels is non-black and non-blue, named the tcolor, change the pixel to tcolor.\n    The function returns the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    ans_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    n, m = ans_grid.shape\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(m):\n            if i == 0 or i == n - 1 or j == 0 or (j == m - 1):\n                if ans_grid[i][j] == black:\n                    tcolor = None\n                    for x in range(max(0, i - 1), min(n, i + 2)):\n                        for y in range(max(0, j - 1), min(m, j + 2)):\n                            if ans_grid[x][y] != black and ans_grid[x][y] != blue:\n                                tcolor = ans_grid[x][y]\n                                break\n                        if tcolor is not None:\n                            break\n                    if tcolor is not None:\n                        ans_grid[i][j] = tcolor\n    return ans_grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see a n*m grid with multiple color pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    ans_grid = change_boundary_pixels(input_grid)\n    ans_grid = change_boundary_and_color_pixels(ans_grid)\n    return ans_grid\ndef change_boundary_and_color_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a n*m grid with multiple color pixels.\n    It goes through all the pixels, and if the current pixel is in the boundary, only consider the pixel within the boundary.\n    If a pixel is black and one of the eight surrounding pixels is non-black and non-blue, named the tcolor, change the pixel to tcolor.\n    Traverse ans_grid row by row, if a row contains three colors or more, and there is only one color, record the color as tcolor. Traverse all the pixels in the row, if a pixel is blue, change the pixel above it to tcolor.\n    The function returns the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    ans_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    n, m = ans_grid.shape\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(m):\n            if i == 0 or i == n - 1 or j == 0 or (j == m - 1):\n                if ans_grid[i][j] == black:\n                    tcolor = None\n                    for x in range(max(0, i - 1), min(n, i + 2)):\n                        for y in range(max(0, j - 1), min(m, j + 2)):\n                            if ans_grid[x][y] != black and ans_grid[x][y] != blue:\n                                tcolor = ans_grid[x][y]\n                                break\n                        if tcolor is not None:\n                            break\n                    if tcolor is not None:\n                        ans_grid[i][j] = tcolor\n    for i in range(n):\n        row = ans_grid[i]\n        colors = set(row)\n        if len(colors) >= 3:\n            for color in colors:\n                if color != blue:\n                    tcolor = color\n                    break\n            for j in range(m):\n                if ans_grid[i][j] == blue and i > 0:\n                    ans_grid[i - 1][j] = tcolor\n    return ans_grid", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see a n*m grid with multiple color pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    ans_grid= `Go through all the pixels,The current pixel is in the boundary, only consider the pixel within the boundary. if a pixel is black and one of the eight surrounding pixels is non-black and non-blue,named the tcolor, change the pixel to tcolor.`(input_grid)\n    ans_grid = `Traverse ans_grid row by row, if a row contains three colors or more, and there is only one color, record the color as tcolor. Traverse all the pixels in the ro